LET US DRINK HISTORY

Here is no ordinary Champagne, but one whose roots go deep into French history. The graceful decanter bottle which houses this remarkable 1971 vintage Champagne, was designed for the Prince Imperial who later became Napoleon IIl—hence the name “Champagne des Princes” The House of de Venoge, established in 1837, received the Royal Warrant from Napoleon Ill during the Second Empire.

What makes this Champagne different and superior?

1) The Champagne is produced predominantly from Pinot Chardonnay grapes grown at de Venoge’s own vineyard, rather than having been purchased from neigh- boring farmers as is usually the practice.

2) The demand for this Champagne has been so intense in France, Belgium and Great Britain, that this shipment marks the first time any has been allocated to the U.S.

3) The de Venoge Champagne has a reputation of pro- viding the most complex taste sensation as compared to any other Champagne in the world. It is not an easy accomplishment to produce a full-bodied, yet delicate Champagne at the same time.

A word about the decanter. It is not Baccarat—but it will remain a happy addition to the home, long after the con- tents have been joyously imbibed. Quantity limited, so please order promptly. (250.50 case)
